{"index": 2094, "diagram_type": "ER", "file": "ER_diagram_19", "question": "How many entities have more than one relation?\nRequired Output Format (strict).\n[start]\n{\"answer\": x}\n[end]\nThe answer MUST be a valid JSON object.\nx must be a number.\n", "response": "Here's how to determine the number of entities with more than one relation:\n\n1.  **Identify the entities:** The entities are the boxes representing tables: `Supplier`, `Customer`, `Item`, `Order`, and `OrderItem`.\n\n2.  **Examine the relationships:** Look at the lines connecting the entities. The symbols at the ends of these lines indicate the type of relationship (one-to-one, one-to-many, many-to-many).\n\n    *   **Supplier** has a relationship with **Item**. This is a one-to-many relationship (one supplier can supply many items).\n    *   **Customer** has a relationship with **Order**. This is a one-to-many relationship (one customer can place many orders).\n    *   **Order** has a relationship with **OrderItem**. This is a one-to-many relationship (one order can have many order items).\n    *   **Item** has a relationship with **OrderItem**. This is a one-to-many relationship (one item can be part of many order items).\n    *   **OrderItem** is a linking table that connects **Order** and **Item**, representing a many-to-many relationship between `Order` and `Item`.\n\n3.  **Count relations per entity:**\n\n    *   **Supplier:** 1 relation (with Item)\n    *   **Customer:** 1 relation (with Order)\n    *   **Item:** 2 relations (with Supplier and OrderItem)\n    *   **Order:** 2 relations (with Customer and OrderItem)\n    *   **OrderItem:** 2 relations (with Order and Item)\n\n4.  **Identify entities with more than one relation:** Based on the count, `Item`, `Order`, and `OrderItem` each have two relations.\n\nTherefore, there are **3** entities that have more than one relation.", "answer": [3], "metadata": {"type": "fill_in_the_blank", "sub_type": "entities_have_more_than_one_relations", "diffi